english:
  title: Record of the Royal Gifts of Vessels to the Sungkyunkwan
  author: Shin Seok-jo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Sungkyunkwan is none other than the Great School of antiquity. Together with the Hall of Worthies and the Hall of Scholarly Compilation, it forms the Three Institutes, truly the beacon and standard of the Way of Letters. When our Taejong, the Virtuous and Steadfast King, dwelt as heir to the throne, he refined his learning in this place and from here embarked upon his official career. His sacred name is inscribed in the memorial records upon the walls—and thus the honor and esteem of the literati, the royal court's regard for this place, surpasses all other institutes.

    There was an old azure-painted bronze bell, a treasure of singular refinement, which the institute cherished greatly. When Taejong ascended the throne, remembering this ancient treasure, he commanded it be placed in a fine case and preserved. He bestowed wine and fruit upon it repeatedly, and henceforth it was revered all the more. At literary gatherings and wine ceremonies, it was always displayed, and scholars would raise toasts to one another in its honor, making it the marvel of every occasion. Yet as years passed, it fell into decay, and all the learned mourned its deterioration.

    In the autumn of the Jeongmyo year, the eighth moon, Jung In-ji, concurrently Rector of the Sungkyunkwan and Minister of Personnel, respectfully presented a detailed petition to the throne. The King immediately bestowed two pairs of white porcelain vessels, a pair each of white and painted bronze bells, their glazes brilliant and lustrous, accompanied by matching cases. The bells themselves were fitted with white metal bindings, wrought with exquisite precision and care. Along with these, generous quantities of wine and meat were granted, extending even to the four subsidiary academies—a singular grace rarely seen across the generations.

    The academy officials led the students to the palace, where they submitted a petition of gratitude, bowing their heads in reverence and dancing with joy. Days later, on the Double Ninth Festival, the Six Ministries and great officials gathered at the Hall of Bright Principles to examine the students. Scholars from all three institutes assembled and displayed the royal gifts. Pouring the sealed wine, they encouraged the masters and raised their cups in mutual celebration. As the gathering grew merry, the Left Premier Ha Yon composed a poem in praise, and the officials answered with verses of their own—thus they honored the royal bounty and sang the praises of the sage's virtue.

    Desiring to preserve this event for eternity, the academy officials asked me to write this record for posterity. I reflect that schools are the source of moral transformation and cultural refinement, the first priority of statecraft. From ancient times—from the Director of the Populace and the Master of Music in the age of Tang and Yu—down through the schools called the jiào, the xiáng, and the xù of the three dynasties, all served to illuminate the relations between people. In later ages, as school policies were maintained or abandoned, the prosperity or decline of customs and the longevity or brevity of the realm depended upon them. How could this not be esteemed?

    Our Taejo possessed the virtues of a sage and, facing the decline of the Koryo age, bore the resolve to restore moral order and revive the Way. He constantly gathered worthy scholars and delighted in studying the Classics and Histories, always taking antiquity as his teacher. When Heaven's mandate came to him and he founded our dynasty, all things lay in their infancy and time was scarce, yet he first built the State Temple and Academy with grand and far-reaching designs. Taejong, continuing his father's work, assumed the responsibility of ruler and teacher through refined and singular learning, conducting himself as an example. Culture and governance flourished. Yet in the midst of countless affairs of state, he did not forget even a humble vessel from his earlier days—and we can only imagine how he spared no effort in all else.

    Today, our present Majesty possesses luminous wisdom and sage-like perception, blessed with heaven's own learning. He honors teachers and values the Way, delights in nurturing talent. His governance and instruction surpass even the three ancient dynasties. Now he honors his forebears' wishes, granting special gifts from the royal treasury, bestowing bounty like spring rains. Will these not shine eternally? Our Way grows ever more weighty, our literary culture ever more radiant, bringing glory greater than in former times and spreading beautiful tales through countless generations. Since the Way of Letters began, few ages have witnessed such splendor.

    The robed scholars gaze in wonder, sharing together in this transformative grace, drenched equally in the dew of heaven's favor. Cultivating virtue and achieving excellence, they become vessels of true use. All people of this age walk in harmony, dancing together in an age of peace and plenty. How then could we cease composing verses like the *Qing'e* and *Fengqi*, those elegant and celebratory hymns? Though I lack talent, I am fortunate to serve in the royal retinue and hold position in the History Office, where song, praise, and chronicle are my very duties. Thus I dare not shrink from my humble capacity, but gladly write this record to place at the head of all these verses.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Taejong (r. 1401-1418) was one of Korea's most accomplished kings, known for strengthening royal authority and promoting Confucian governance.
  - key: ''
    value: The Three Institutes (tripartite bureaucratic structure) consisted of the Sungkyunkwan (National Academy), the Hall of Worthies, and the Hall of Scholarly Compilation, representing the highest intellectual institutions of the Joseon dynasty.
  - key: ''
    value: The azure-painted bell mentioned here was a treasured ritual vessel symbolizing the continuity between Taejong's scholarly past and his royal present.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Way of Letters' (斯文) refers to Confucian civilization and moral learning, considered the foundation of good governance.
  - key: ''
    value: The author held concurrent positions in both the court administration and the royal history compilation office, which gave him authority to compose official records and commemorative writings.
